			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Alternative to Hot Keys<a name="44895"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jun 8 04 6:54 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hey there. I've been visiting the site for a while now, but I decided I just had to share my method of song twisting with everyone, so I registered.
<br />

<br />
See, I can't stand hotkeys for songs. The reason is, you have to keep changing them whenever you change your songs. They also leave little room for other important hotkeys like /assist or your /gsay YAH! I'm going to DIE! Get %O off me!!! button.
<br />

<br />
What I prefer to do instead is <i>change the key settings</i>. So go to &quot;Options&quot; and under &quot;Keyboard&quot; go to the Cast Spell heading. Now set each cast gem to it's appropriate number on the keyboard (i.e. Cast Gem 1 set it to 1 on the keyboard).
<br />

<br />
The 1-0 keys were previously the macro hotkeys, so you have to reset those. Set them to F1 - F10. Or alternatively you can set the cast gems to the F# keys and the macros can be left as 1-0. Whatever you do, I recommend you set to the F# keys the one which you will not want to have to look down at. Since the F#s are spaced apart in groups of 4 on your keyboard, this lets you feel where the keys are better.
<br />

<br />
You'll have to do some more work resetting your keys so that nothing conflicts. It's a fair bit of work in the beginning, but after everything is set there will be no more work at all, and you'll have the convenience of being able to switch the songs you're playing on a dime. I even set the spellbook to the ` key so that I can access it quickly.
<br />

<br />
So now you twist your songs by pressing the number keys twice (once to stop song, second to start the new song). You cycle through 1, 2, 3, and back again (I have a slow computer so I only twist 3<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-8.gif" border="0" alt="Expressionless" hspace="2" />) If the situation changes, adjust your cycle so that it's 1, 2, 4... or move your hand down so that it's 2, 3, 4 or 3, 4, 5. Whatever. This makes the ordering of songs in the spell bank more important.
<br />

<br />
Many people are used to having several hotkey banks full of crap, so they can Shift-# to it. When you have your keys set up like I do, you can still set it to Shift-F# and all, but you'll find that you don't need to as often, because you're using a lot less macros. Often times 10 macros is all you need, and the different banks are simply there for different situations (Solo macro bank, Group macro bank, Puller macro bank, etc.).
<br />

<br />
This may not relate too much to song twisting, but incidentally I also reset my movement keys so that I use the old w = forward, a = left, d = right, s = backwards setup. I also have autorun set to q, cycle nearest NPC set to e, and autoattack set to r. So my left hand is all in one place and can do anything. Twisting songs while running is easy this way. So is attacking, since it means I simply tap e, then r with two fingers and I'm on autoattack with the nearest enemy.
<br />

<br />
Of course, If you've been plaing EQ with the default settings all this time then it will probably take you a bit of time to get used to the new keyboard settings, but once you do you'll be a very dexterous bard player.
<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-11.gif" border="0" alt="Cool" hspace="2" /></span></td>
